<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920121-0099</DOCNO><DOCID>920121-0099.</DOCID><HL>   York International   Says Fourth Period   Held No Surprises</HL><DATE>01/21/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   YRK</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)</IN><NS>EXCLUSIVE INTERVIEW WITH CHIEF EXECUTIVES (CEO)EARNINGS PROJECTIONS (ERP)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- York International Corp. said it expectsfourth-quarter and 1991 earnings to be in line with analysts'estimates of 32 cents and $1.30 a share on a pro forma basis.   Robert N. Pokelwaldt, president and chief executiveofficer, said &quot;there will be no surprises&quot; when the companyreports results of its first quarter as a public companyagain. Results are expected to be reported in mid-February.Sales have been increasing at about a 13% annual rate, andthat is expected to continue, said Mr. Pokelwaldt and Dean T.DuCray, York's chief financial officer. They declined toforecast fourth-quarter or full-year sales, although Mr.Pokelwaldt said &quot;we came in close to plan&quot;; for the ninemonths of last year, third quarter sales rose 13% to $414million and increased 9% to $1.19 billion for the period.</LP><TEXT>   York became a public company again in October with aninitial offering of 10.7 million shares, priced at $23 each,raising proceeds of $261 million which were used to retiredebt raised in the company's leveraged buy-out in 1988. York,prior to the buy-out, was a 1986 spinoff of Borg-Warner Corp.   The two executives were in New York to speak to theanalysts who follow the company, and said they hope more WallStreet firms begin investment research on York. Mr.Pokelwaldt noted that one problem in finding more analysts isthat &quot;we're the only single play out there&quot; in therefrigeration and air-conditioning business. Its maincompetitors in the large refrigeration equipment buisness,Carrier Corp. and Trane Co., are both owned by big parents --United Technologies Corp. and American Standard Corp.,respectively.   York also produces heating and ventilation equipment. Forthe residential and small-office market, there are severalAmerican makers and now a slew of Japanese makers ofportables, Mr. Pokelwaldt said.</TEXT></DOC>